      "question": "What is the judicial process for a crime in Belgium?",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "An offense is the lightest form of a crime, typically judged by the police court. Examples include noise disturbance at night, public intoxication, and traffic violations."
        },
        {
                          "type": "image",
                          "url": "https://globalaccesstojustice.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/belgium-graph02.jpg"
                 },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "A misdemeanor is a more serious crime than an offense and carries heavier penalties. The correctional court handles misdemeanors. Examples include theft, abuse of trust, fraud, and assault and battery."
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "Felonies are the most severe crimes and are adjudicated by the court of assizes. Examples include sexual assault of a minor, rape, and murder."
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "Several procedures can initiate a criminal prosecution: the police may detect a crime or catch someone in the act, individuals can file complaints with the police or public prosecutor, victims can become civil parties in the case, and injured parties can summon suspected offenders directly to court for minor offenses or misdemeanors."
        },
        {
                          "type": "image",
                          "url": "https://admin.expatica.com/be/wp-content/uploads/sites/4/1970/01/police-brussels-pointing.jpg"
                 },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "The criminal investigation serves to gather evidence and compile a case file. Two methods are available: an investigative inquiry led by the public prosecutor or a judicial inquiry conducted by an investigating judge."
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "During an investigative inquiry, the prosecutor collaborates with the police. If privacy-invasive measures are required (e.g., a house search), an investigating judge is involved. Afterward, the prosecutor decides on the case: close it, propose a settlement, initiate mediation, or prosecute the suspect."
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "In judicial inquiries, the investigating judge handles complex cases requiring special measures (e.g., wiretapping). The judge may place suspects under temporary detention or release them under specific conditions. A supervisory chamber oversees the process and decides the case's next steps."
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "Criminal trials typically occur in the police court for offenses, the correctional court for misdemeanors, or the court of assizes for felonies. At trial, the prosecutor presents the case, the defendant is represented, and victims may seek damages. The judge or jury determines guilt and issues a verdict."
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "Verdicts can include acquittal, monetary fines, or imprisonment. Sentences may involve electronic monitoring, probation, or suspension under conditions. The court can also rule on insanity, leading to institutionalization."
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "After the verdict, parties can appeal or seek a retrial in higher courts. In cases of legal errors or procedural mistakes, an appeal to the Court of Cassation is possible."
        },
        {
          "type": "source",
          "url": "https://www.justice.belgium.be"
        },
        {
          "type": "image",
          "url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/3/3b/Palais_de_Justice_Bruxelles.jpg"
        }
      ]
